year = "1962",
issn = "0029-5582",
doi = "https://doi.org/10.1016/0029-5582(62)90345-0",
url = "http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0029558262903450",
author = "F. Perey and B. Buck",
abstract = "An energy independent non-local optical potential for the elastic scattering of neutrons from nuclei is proposed and the wave-equation solved numerically in its full integro-differential form. The non-local kernel is assumed seperable into a potential form factor times a Gaussian non-locality. The potential form factor, of argument 1/2r+r'), is that of a real Saxon form plus an imaginary term having the shape of the derivative of a Saxon form. A real local spin-orbit potential of the usual Thomas form is included. The parameters of the potential obtained solely from the fitting of the differential cross sections for lead at 7 MeV and 14.5 MeV are used unchanged to calculate the elastic differential cross sections, total and reaction cross sections and polarizations on some elements ranging from Al to Pb at various energies from 0.4 MeV to 24 MeV. The S-wave strength functions and the effective scattering radius Râ² are also calculated with the same parameters. The parameters in the usual notations are: real potential V = 71 MeV, r = 1.22 fm, a = 0.65 fm; surface imaginary potential W = 15 MeV, a = 0.47 fm; non-locality Î² = 0.85 fm; spin-orbit potential, using the nucleon mass in the Thomas form, Uso = 1300 MeV. The energy independence of the potential parameters allows the compound elastic scattering to be included approximately at energies below 4 MeV. The calculations are compared to the data over the whole energy range, and the quality of the agreement with the data is found to be comparable to that obtained previously with energy-dependent local optical potentials. A âlocal WKBâ approximation to the integro-differential equation is derived and found to give an approximate relation between the non-local potential and the equivalent local optical potential."
}

